bib_record.title: Isotopic production cross sections of spallation- evaporation residues from reactions of 238-U (1A-GeV) with deuterium.

free_txt: Institut de physique nucleaire.
Dapnia/SPhN, CEA/Saclay.
Main reference
Transient and quasistationary
dissipative effects in the fission flux across the
barrier in 1*A*GeV U-238 on deuterium reactions.
prelim.publication
The corrections included the angular acceptance of the
FRS, the selection of atomic charge states, the losses
by secondary reactions in the different layers of
matter along the FRS, the dead time of the data
acquisition system and the additional production of
residual nuclides in the target windows.
Finally, the measured cross sections were also
corrected for the multiple reactions that take place
inside the target.
-By authors. Isotopic identification of residues with
z<70 were identified by measuring the energy loss
delta-E with multi-sampling ionization chambers
'Music'  placed at the exit of the FRS.
The measured energy-loss value was corrected for ion
velocity  dependence,  ion-recombination in the gas and
the border effects of the electric field.
For z>70- contamination due to charge states produced
inside the FRS and the loss in resolution in delta-E
measurements with the'Music'chambers due to stochastic
charge-state changes within the gas.
The method adopted here used a profiled aluminum
achromatic energy degrader, placed at the  intermediate
focal plane of the FRS and the measurement of energy
losses in two 'Music' chambers, combined adequately.
-By authors-.The final production cross section of the
different projectile residues were obtained from the
production yields normalized to the number of atoms
per surface unit of the target and the beam intensity.
Two plastic scintillators, one placed at the
intermediate focal plane of the FRS and another at the
final focal plane about 2-m beyond the end of the FRS
vacuum pipe.
The drift-time measured with the multi-sampling
ionization chambers were used to define the tracking
angle.
The accuracy of the isotopic production cross sections
was determined from the uncertainties of the production
yields, beam intensity and target thickness.
The uncertainty of the measured production cross
section was less than 6% statistical and less than 15%
systematic for 85% of the data, for the charge range
covered by this experiments (z=92 to z=58). For some
of elements with z below 70 an additional systematic
uncertainty accounts for the separation between
fragmentation and fission production. The most neutron-
deficient isotopes can also show larger uncertainties
due to the contribution of multiple reactions.
.The error in beam intensity is 4%.
.The error in target thickness variation was
less than 1% for 80% of the projectiles and less than
3% for total distribution. The influence of tiny
temperature fluctuations on the density of the target
during the experiment was negligible.
.Statistical uncertainty.
The systematic uncertainty.
The liquified deuterium with mass thickness of 200-
mg/cm**2, was encapsulated in a container with
Ti-windows, total thickness 36.32-mg/cm**2, and
surrounded by Mylar-Al, 9.7-mg/cm**2 for thermal
insulation. A second target, with the same components
and thicknesses as the container, was used to determine
the additional production of the residual nuclei in the
windows of the cryogenic target.
